# Project overview

**Golem Engine** is a Go module that helps you build multiplayer game backends: a small **runtime** (`golem`) with a tick-based game loop, entity registry, serialized per-tick deltas, and static world data, plus a **code generator** (`golem-bake`) that reads `golem.yaml`, entity YAML under the configured `entity_schema` directory, and world YAML under `schemas/world/` (by default) and emits protobuf and integration code from embedded templates under `codegen/templates/`.

## Layout

| Path | Role |
|------|------|
| `cmd/golem-bake/` | CLI entrypoint: `golem-bake` runs codegen from the project root |
| `schema/` | `golem.yaml` + entity/command/world YAML loading and template data (`Config`, `EntityData`, `WorldTypeData`, naming helpers) |
| `codegen/` | `Bake`, embedded templates, integration targets (e.g. go-server, go-client, js-client) |
| `golem/` | Game loop: `Server`, tick/delta hooks, world data; re-exports `Entity`, `WorldStore`, and related interfaces for generated code |
| `golem/registry/` | Thread-safe `Registry` and `Entity` interface |
| `golem/world/` | Thread-safe `Store` for static world data; `Data` interface for generated world types |
| `golem-go-client/` | Native Go client runtime: `GameClient`, WebSocket/WebTransport channels, generated-manager contracts, protobuf helpers |
| `golem-ebiten/` | Ebiten helper package: client lifecycle, view/drawable contracts, generated bridge support |
| `golem-js/` | JS/TS runtime npm package (`golem-engine`): `GameClient`, `PbWriter`/`PbReader` codec |

## Subsystem organization

- **Tooling (`golem-bake`):** `cmd/` + `schema/` + `codegen/`. **Runtime (library):** `golem/` + `golem/registry/` + `golem/world/`.
- **`golem/registry` and `golem/world` do not import `golem`** (loop/API). Prefer depending on `golem/registry` when work is storage/entities only, and `golem/world` for world data only.
- **Cursor:** `.cursor/rules/subsystem-*.mdc` use globs; when you change a subsystem’s layout or responsibilities, update the matching rule (description, boundaries, globs).

Consumer repos hold `golem.yaml` and schema YAML at their root (paths from config); this repo may omit them.

## Documentation rule

When **adding** a new function or method, add a **brief** comment describing what it does (Go: `// Name ...` godoc above the declaration). When **editing** an existing function, **update its comment** if behavior, side effects, or callers’ expectations change.

**User-facing docs** (Docusaurus Markdown under `docs/public/`) follow `.cursor/rules/documentation.mdc`.

**Inside functions:** comment sparingly. Prefer **why** (invariant, workaround, API quirk, perf tradeoff) over **what** the next line already says. Skip inner comments when the code is self-explanatory—many functions need **none**.
